# Parallel Execution

1️⃣ Parallel Execution in Playwright
Parallel Execution means running multiple test cases at the same time instead of one after another.
It helps to reduce total test execution time.
Example:
    Execution Type & Time taken
    ----------------------------
    1. Sequantial (1 by 1) -> 30 minutes
    2. Parallel (multiple tests simultaneously) -> 8-10 minutes
So Parallel test execution is mainly used to speed up automation test execution.

2️⃣ Why Parallel Execution is Important (Interview Point)
In real projects we may have:
    1. 500 +
    2. 1000 +
    3. 5000 + testcases
Running them sequantially will take hours.

Parallel execution helps to :
    1. Reduce execution time
    2. Improve CI/CD pipeline speed
    3. Run tests on mutliple browsers/devices simultaneously
    4. Detect failures faster

3️⃣ How Parallel Execution Works (Concept)
When parallel execution is enabled:
    1. Multiple test workers are created
    2. Each worker runs separate test cases
    3. Each worker launches separate browser instances

Flow:
    Test Suite
        │
        ├── Worker 1 → Test A → Browser Instance
        ├── Worker 2 → Test B → Browser Instance
        ├── Worker 3 → Test C → Browser Instance
        └── Worker 4 → Test D → Browser Instance
All tests run simultaneously.

4️⃣ Parallel Execution in Playwright Python
Playwright Python uses pytest framework
Parallel execution is enabled using:
    pytest-xdist plugin

5️⃣ Installing Parallel Execution Plugin
Install pytest-xdist
    pip Install pytest-xdist

Veirfy instllation
    pyest --help

You should see options like:
    -n
    --dist
    --tx

6️⃣ Running Tests in Parallel
Basic syntax:
    pytest -n <number of workers>

Example:
    pytest -n 4

Meaning:
    -> 4 workers will run tests simultaneously

Example:
    tests/
        test_login.py
        test_checkout.py
        test_search.py
        test_profile.py

Execution:
    Worker1 → test_login
    Worker2 → test_checkout
    Worker3 → test_search
    Worker4 → test_profile

7️⃣ Run Tests Using Maximum CPU Cores
You can automatically use all CPU cores.
    pytest -n auto

Example:
    If system has 8 cores
        pytest -n auto
pytest creates 8 workers

8️⃣ Parallel Execution Example (Playwright + Pytest)
Example test:
    import pytest
from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright

def test_google():
    with sync_playwright() as p:
        browser = p.chromium.launch()
        page = browser.new_page()
        page.goto("https://google.com")
        assert "Google" in page.title()
        browser.close()

Run Parallel:
    pytest -n 3

Output example:
    gw0 [1] / gw1 [1] / gw2 [1]

    3 workers running tests

9️⃣ Parallel Execution with Multiple Browsers
Example:
    test_chromium.py
    test_firefox.py
    test_webkit.py

Run
    pytest -n 3

Worker will run:
    Worker1 → Chromium test
    Worker2 → Firefox test
    Worker3 → Webkit test
This enables cross-browser parallel testing.

🔟 Parallel Execution with Test Files
Parallel execution normally happens at:
    1. Test file level
    2. Test function level

Example file:
    test_login.py

    def test_valid_login():
        pass

    def test_invalid_login():
        pass

    def test_empty_login():
        pass

Workers may executes:
    Worker1 → test_valid_login
    Worker2 → test_invalid_login
    Worker3 → test_empty_login

1️⃣1️⃣ Test Isolation in Parallel Execution
Each test must be independent
Why?
Parallel test run simultaneously.

Best example ❌:
    Test1 → creates user
    Test2 → uses same user

If Test2 runs first → test fails.
Good example ✔
    Each test should:
        1. Create it own data
        2. Use separate browser
        3. Not depend on other tests
    
1️⃣2️⃣ Browser Isolation in Playwright
Playwright ensures isolation using:
Browser context
Each test gets:
    Browser
        ├── Context1 → Test1
        ├── Context2 → Test2
        ├── Context3 → Test3

This prevents:
    Cookie conflicts
    Session conflicts
    Data sharing issues

1️⃣3️⃣ Parallel Execution in CI/CD
Parallel execution is heavily used in:
    1. Jenkins
    2. GitHub actions
    3. GitLab CI
    4. Azure DevOps

Example:
    CI Pipeline
        │
        ├── Worker1 → Login tests
        ├── Worker2 → Checkout tests
        ├── Worker3 → Search tests
        └── Worker4 → Profile tests

This reduces pipeline time drastically.

1️⃣4️⃣ Common Problems in Parallel Execution
1. Shared Test Data
Example:
    Multiple tests using same user

Solution:
    1. create unique users
    2. Use test data generator

2. Database Conflicts
Example:
    Two tests updating same record

Solution:
    Use separate test data

3. File Access Issues
Example:
    Two tests writing same file

Solution:
    Use unique filenames

4. Hardcoded Waits
Example:
    time.sleep(10)

This slows parallel tests

Solution:
    Use playwright auto-waiting.

